3 Distributions and relationships between variables¶

3.1 Univariate Analysis using Pandas profile¶

The pandas profile module allows to perform univariate data analysis

In [26]:
# get pandas profile report
pandas_profiling.ProfileReport(data)










    
    





















    
    















    
    





















    
    















    
    
















    
    
Out[26]:




























From this analysis we can conclude:


    

  •  Product:  There are 3 different treadmill models: TM195, TM498 and TM798. Being TM195 (44.4%) the most popular and TM798 (22.2%) the less popular
    • 

  •  Age:  The age distribution is skewed to the left. The mean is 28.7 years, the median is 26 and the mode is 25. The min is 18 and the max is 50
    • 

  •  Gender:  There are more male users (57.8%) than female users (42.2%)
    • 

  •  Education:  The mean is 15.6 years, the median and the mode are 16 years
    • 

  •  Marital Status:  There are more partnered users (59.4%) than single users (40.6%)
    • 

  •  Usage:  The usage distribution is skewed to the left. The mean is 3.5, the median and mode are 3
    • 

  •  Fitness:  The majority of users are very fit (category 5) and represent (53.9%) of the sample
    • 

  •  Income:  The income distribution is skewed to the left. The mean is 53719, the median is 50596 and the mode 45480
    • 

  •  Miles:  The miles distribution is skewed to the left. The mean is 103, the median is 94 and the mode 85
    •

3.3 Analysis by Gender¶
In this section we are going to analyze the relationships between Gender and other variables


3.3.1 Usage and Fitness¶
The boxplot below shows the quartiles of Usage for the different Fitness categories for Male and Female











In [30]:



     


# create boxplot chart
sns.boxplot(data['Fitness'], data['Usage'], hue=data['Gender']);



     


















    
    



























There is a positive correlation between Fitness and Usage for both Gender. Although, for Males with high Fitness Score (4 and 5) there is a higher variance in Usage compared with Females with same Fitness Score











3.3.2 Usage and Miles¶
The boxplot below shows the quartiles of Miles for different Usage levels for Male and Female











In [31]:



     


# create boxplot chart
sns.boxplot(data['Usage'], data['Miles'], hue=data['Gender']);



     


















    
    



























There is a positive correlation between Miles and Usage for both Gender. The range of Miles run by Males is higher than Females for Usage of 4 times per week. However, the range of Miles run by Females is higher than Males for Usage of 5 times per week. There are no data for Females with Usage of 7 times per week.











For this analysis, it is interesting to analyze distribution of the ratio between Miles and Usage by Gender- using violinplot chart











In [32]:



     


# new Series with the ratio between Miles and Usage
data['Miles_Usage'] = data['Miles']/data['Usage'] 



     















In [33]:



     


# create violinplot chart
sns.violinplot(data['Gender'], data['Miles_Usage']);



     


















    
    



























This violinplot shows that Males run on average higher miles per usage than Females

4 Conclusions and recommendations¶










4.1 Customer profile¶
From the previous univariate and multivariate analysis we can conclude that each product have an specific characteristics of customers. Product TM798 in the top tier. Product TM498 in the medium tier. Product TM195 in the bottom tier.


4.1.1 Product TM798¶
Although, TM798 is the less popular product (22.2%), there is a clear profile of the users with the product:


    

  • Mostly Male (33 Male vs 7 Female)
    • 

  • Mostly Partnered (23 Partnered vs 17 Single)
    • 

  • Higher Income (Avg 75441.57 - Male 75825.03, Female 73633.85). Partnered customers have higher average income than single customers (82047.17 Partnered vs 66504.58 Single)
    • 

  • Higher Education (Avg 17.32 years, Male 17.2, Female 17.8)
    • 

  • Higher Fitness level (Avg 4.62, Male 4.63, Female 4.57)
    • 

  • Higher Usage (Avg 4.77 times - Male 4.72, Female 5)
    • 

  • Higher Miles (Avg 166.9 - Male 164, Female 180 - Partnered 183, Single 145) 
    • 



4.1.2 Product TM498¶
TM498 is in the middle in terms of number of users (33.4%). The characteristics of the customers are:


    

  • There is no important difference between number of Males and Females users (31 Male vs 29 Female). There is also no important difference in other variables between Males and Females.
    • 

  • Mostly Partnered (36 Partnered vs 24 Single)
    • 

  • Medium/Low Income (Avg 48973.65)
    • 

  • Medium Education (Avg 15.11 years)
    • 

  • Medium/Low Fitness level (Avg 2.9)
    • 

  • Medium Usage (Avg 3 times)
    • 

  • Medium Miles (Avg 87.9, Partnered 90, Single 84.7)
    • 

  • Partnered users are in average older than single customers (30.2 Partnered vs 26.9 Single)
    • 



4.1.3 Product TM195¶
TM195 is the most popular product (44.4%). The characteristics of the customers are:


    

  • Same number of Males and Females (40 customers each group). There is no important difference in other variables between Male and Female
    • 

  • Mostly Partnered (48 Partnered vs 32 Single)
    • 

  • Medium/Low Income (Avg 46418)
    • 

  • Medium Education (Avg 15.03 years)
    • 

  • Medium/Low Fitness level (Avg 2.9)
    • 

  • Medium Usage (Avg 3 times)
    • 

  • Low Miles (Avg 82.7, Partnered 77, Single 91, Female 76, Male 89)
    • 



4.2 Recommendations¶
The company can target each product for different type of customers.


    

  • Product TM798 should be targeted at customers with higher Income and Education level. This costumers are going to present higher Fitness level and Usage with this product.
    • 

  • Product TM498 should be targeted at Partnered customers with medium Income. This costumers are going to run more miles in average than Single customers
    • 

  • Product TM195 should be targeted at Male and Single customers with medium/low Income. This costumers are going to run more miles in average than Partnered and Female customers.
    •
